<TITLE> Quader celebrates indigenous Bangladesh </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Cox's Bazar, Jan 30 (bdnews24.com)The civil aviation and tourism minister on Friday urged all to protect the uniqueness of indigenous communities of the country. "Bangladesh has become colourful, thanks to the indigenous communities," GM Qader said. Calling them "our treasure trove", the minister said they enriched Bangladesh in its cultural heritage and diversity. His remarks came in his speech at the inaugural session of a day-long 'Adivasi Fair 2009' at the country's tourist capital Cox's Bazar sea beach in the morning. Bangladesh Parjatan Corporation and private television 'Channel I' co-organised the fair. Speaking of his commitment to develop tourism, he said he would do all he can and called for promotion of domestic tourism. "Law and order situation in the tourist destinations of Bangladesh is much better than those of other countries." Some 12 indigenous communities from the Chittagong Hill Tracts and Cox's Bazar including Chakma, Marma, Pangkhua, Bom, Murong, Rakhain participated in the fair and performed their traditional dances and songs. A number of government and non-government organisations also participated. bdnew
